    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Up, Down, In and Out in Beverly Hills: Rats'' (front page, Sept. 17) raises the question: Are the chickens (or rats, in this case) coming home to roost for the residents of Southern California?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Up, Down, In and Out in Beverly Hills: Rats'' (front page, Sept. 17) raises the question: Are the chickens (or rats, in this case) coming home to roost for the residents of Southern California?</p>
        <p>A prolonged period of drought and consistently warmer winters, apparently a result of global warming, has made the region more hospitable to rodents.</p>
        <p>California is the world's sixth-largest contributor to global warming. Maybe this current plague should be taken as a sign of the disruptive power of climate change.</p>
        <p>The time to invest in solar, wind and other sources of renewable energy is now.</p>
        <p>BYRON KAHR  Venice, Calif., Sept. 17, 2002</p>
      </block>
